Introduction

When it comes to transportation, people’s safety is and always will be our top priority. With the rise of self driving cars, we must re-examine our current safety measures and introduce new ones that will better match the future of driving. While there were many car safety features introduced in the past decades, the airbag is often considered one of the most important piece of safety equipment. However, it is vital to study the situations when airbags are the most effective and what the drawbacks are. Despite the fact that this technology saved numerous lives, there were also accidents when it was a contributing factor to inguries and even fatalities.

Let’s begin the research by looking at the trend in the accidents over the years.

Accidents per year

ggplot(df)+aes(x=yearacc)+geom_bar(fill='blue')+ggtitle("Accidents per year")

The accidents have always been high in number but we can see from the above graph that there was a slight decrease in the number of accidents during 2000 and 2001 but then it again showed an upward trend in 2002.

From our dataset, the total number of people were 26,217 out of which 25,037 were accident survivors while 1,180 succumbed to the injuries. Based on these data, the overall survival rate can be calculated as the ratio of the total number of survivors out of the total people in the dataset i.e 25,037/26,217 = 0.95499 which indicates that there is 95.5% survival rate among the people who met with accidents.

Which is a really good percentage when compared to the number of accidents per year.

Also, from the graph we can see that the number of survivors are very high even though the number of accidents are high.

In the second graph we can see that, when comparing the number of fatalities with respect to vehicles having airbag or not, we can see that irrespective of the vehicle having an airbag or not, majority of the population have survived the accident though there is a slight increase in the number of fatalities in vehicles not having an airbag.

In graph 4, we observe that when the airbags were unavailable, the accidents caused due to this was more. We can observe one strange trend here that when the cars had airbags and the airbags were deployed, the number of accidents were higher as compared to those cars where the airbags weren’t deployed. The people most at risk of death from airbag deployment are actually children and small adults, because their bodies can’t take the force. Moreover, most children ride in child safety seats, which aren’t designed for use with airbags. Seat type and positioning can also put a child at risk.

Graph 5 shows that in maximum cars where airbags were deployed had the occupants below 25 years of age.

CONCLUSION

Prior to our analysis, we were under the assumption that airbags and seatbelts protected people from injuries and even death but during the course of our analysis we observed quite a few strange trends. From this cases analysis, we can observe a few surprising insights. Initially, when cars were manufactured without airbags and seat-belts, the number of fatalities were high which is quite obvious as there was no safety mechanisms in the vehicle. But from 1986, cars were manufactured with airbags and seat belts and it was expected that with more safety measures, the number of fatalities should have reduced but that was not the case. This can be attributed to the fact that majority of the people who succumbed to the injuries were kids and young adults who were not able to take the impact of the accidents.It was also observed that amongst vehicles manufactured in early 1960s and 1970s, limited vehicles met with an accident having speed more than 40 km/h (Only 30 from years 1956 to 1970) whereas the count is very high for vehicles in late 1980s and early 1990s (2889 from years 1990 to 2002). Even though the number of accidents were more, the overall survival rate has been quite high that is, 95.5%. The basic assumption that wearing seatbelts protects a person from injuries and that higher the speed, higher is the risk of fatality has been confirmed. Another observation was that female drivers generally prefer to stay within the speed limit.
